  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential imprisonment of up to 20 years\n- Substantial criminal fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Potential forfeiture of assets used in or derived from the illegal activity\n\n2. Civil Penalties:\n- Additional monetary penalties\n- Potential civil asset seizure\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n\n3. Specific Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- Penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and intent\n\n4. Aggravating Factors:\n- Penalties may increase if laundering is connected to other serious crimes\n- International or large-scale money laundering can lead to more severe consequences\n\n5. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Damage to professional reputation\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific case details, amount of money involved, and whether the offense is prosecuted at federal or state level.\n\nNote: This information is general guidance and should not be considered legal advice. Consult a qualified attorney for specific legal interpretation.",
